{{For|the song composed by Michel Mauléart Monton with lyrics from a poem by Oswald Durand|Choucoune (song)}}

'''Cabane Choucoune''', is a [[cabaret]] and [[Thatching|thatch-roofed]] club in [[Pétion-Ville]], [[Haiti]].<ref name="Black_Enterprise">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t18EAAAAMBAJ&pg |title=Island Music: Where to Hear it, Dance to it |editor=Press |date=May 1984 |page=97 |publisher=Black Enterprise |volume=14 (No. 10) |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JxtnAAAAMAAJ&q |title=The West Indies and Their Future |editor=Guérin, Daniel |page=72 |year=1961 |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> It was built on 8 December 1940 by Max Ewald.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uv9mAAAAMAAJ&q |title=Conjonction, Issues 156-163 |editor=Press |year=1983 |page=29 |publisher=Institut français d'Haiti |accessdate=14 April 2017}} {{fr}}</ref> It is known as one of the best [[méringue]] dance clubs.<ref name="Black_Enterprise"/> Historically, it has featured Haitian artists such as [[Nemours Jean-Baptiste]] as well as international entertainers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewRsAAAAMAAJ&q |title=All the Best in the Caribbean, Including Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands |editor1=Clark, Sydney|editor2=Zellers, Margaret |page=141 |date=1 January 1972 |isbn=9780396065272 |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3RbzX4PjxtgC&pg=PA142#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Historical Dictionary of Haiti |author= Michael R. Hall|page=142 |publisher= Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0810878105 }}</ref>

The construction appears like an inverted ice cream cone, that is high-peaked with a thatched cupola on top. From a distance, it resembles a chief's African jungle [[hut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xGILAQAAMAAJ&dq |title=Escape to the West Indies: A Guidebook to the Islands of the Caribbean |editor=Smith, Bradley |page=202 |year=1956 |publisher=A. A. Knopf |accessdate=14  April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6wowAQAAIAAJ&q |title=Cue: The Weekly Magazine of New York Life |editor=Press |page=43 |year=1955 |publisher=Cue Publishing Company |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref>

It is located about 500 metres up the mountains behind [[Port-au-Prince]], in Pétion-Ville, home to the country's elite.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yi8dAQAAMAAJ&q |title=Quadrant, Volume 31 |editor=Press |page=59 |year=1987 |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref>

