{{Infobox theatre group|formed={{Start date and age|2001|08|18|df=yes}}|name=Vesturport|location=[[Reykjavík]], [[Iceland]]|homepage={{URL|vesturport.com}}}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
'''Vesturport''' is an [[Iceland]]ic [[theatre]] group, founded on 18 August 2001.<ref name="history">{{Cite web|url=http://vesturport.com/about/vesturport-history/|title=Vesturport Story|last=|first=|date=|website=Vesturport|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> The group has performed plays in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and [[Australia]]. In 2011, it received the [[Europe Prize New Theatrical Realities]] for its complete work, innovative character and originality.<ref name="europe theatre prize">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2011/apr/20/europe-theatre-prize-peter-stein-vesturport|title=Europe theatre prize: Peter Stein seethes and Vesturport vaults|last=Billington|first=Michael|date=2011-04-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>
==Overview== On the day that the theatre group was founded, the play ''Discopigs'' was performed in [[Reykjavík]]. Over the next three years the group performed the plays ''Key around the neck'', ''Titus'' and ''Mr. Man''.<ref name="history" /> Its first performance outside of Iceland was ''Romeo and Juliet'', on 18 November 2004 in Playhouse Theatre, London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisistheatre.com/londonshows/romeoandjuliet.html#vesturport|title=Romeo and Juliet: Love is in the Air|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=thisistheatre.com|archiveurl=|archivedate=|dead-url=|accessdate=2017-08-02}}</ref> Romeo and Juliet was subsequently shown in Germany, Poland, Norway and Finland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vesturport.com/theater/romeo-juliet/|title=Romeo & Juliet|last=|first=|date=|website=Vesturport|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> In 2004 the group premiered the Icelandic play ''Brim'' and it received the Icelandic Gríman award for the best theatre script.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.griman.is/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=77:handhafar-grnnar-2004&catid=13:vernahafar&Itemid=84|title=Handhafar Grímuverðlauna 2004|last=|first=|date=|website=www.griman.is|language=is-is|trans-title=2004 Griman Award Winners|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> On 30 April 2004 the group premiered the first theatre play of Víkingur Kristinsson, ''Shopping mall shattered''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vesturport.com/theater/mall-shattered/|title=Shopping Mall Shattered|last=|first=|date=|website=Vesturport|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> In 2008 the group premiered the plays ''Together'' and ''Love'' in [[Reykjavík City Theatre]] and ''Dubbeldelush'' in Akureyri Theatre. On 15 October the group premiered the play ''Woyzeck'' in the [[Howard Gilman Opera House]] in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.antilabelblog.com/?p=732|title=US debut of Iceland’s Vesturport Theatre’s Production of Woyzeck Features Original Music by Nick Cave and Warren Ellis|last=|first=|date=2008-08-28|website=ANTI-|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727132623/http://www.antilabelblog.com/?p=732|archive-date=2011-07-27|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> A year later the group premiered the play ''Metamorphosis'' in [[Tasmania]] in a collaboration with [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)|Lyric Hammersmith]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/reviews/tendays/metamorphosis--lyric-hammersmith/vesturport-2394.html|title=Metamorphosis {{!}} Lyric Hammersmith / Vesturport|last=Kidd|first=Briony|date=2009-03-31|website=Australian Stage|language=en-gb|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> The group then collaborated with [[Nick Cave]] and [[Warren Ellis (musician)|Warren Ellis]] to compose music for the play Faust,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/oct/03/faust-nick-cave-vesturport-review|title=Faust|last=Billington|first=Michael|date=2010-10-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> with planned performances in Berlin, Hamburg and London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.visir.is/g/2009248951555|title=Vesturport og Nick Cave gera nýja leikgerð af Faust|last=|first=|date=2009-07-03|work=Visir|access-date=2017-08-02|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=Icelandic|trans-title=Vesturport and Nick Cave Create a New Adaptation of Faust}}</ref> In 2010 the group received favorable criticism from the [[New York Times]] for the play ''Metamorphosis'', which increased the popularity of the group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/03/theater/reviews/03metamorphosis.html|title=Kafka’s ‘Metamorphosis’ at Brooklyn Academy - Review|last=Rooney|first=David|date=2010-12-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.visir.is/g/2010768056779/amerika-opnast-fyrir-vesturport|title=Ameríka opnast fyrir Vesturport|last=|first=|date=2010-12-04|work=Visir|access-date=2017-08-02|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=Icelandic|trans-title=America Opens for Vesturport}}</ref> A year later the group started collaborating with Tony-award winner [[Robin de Levita]] on ''Metamorphosis'', ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'', ''Loce the Musical'', The Brothers Karamazov, and Mad Alice, with planned performances in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/vesturport-theatre-group-and-robin-de-levita-hope-to-bring-mad-alice-love-the-musical-to-the-us-com-175991|title=Vesturport Theatre Group and Robin de Levita Hope to Bring Mad Alice, Love the Musical to the U.S.|last=Gans|first=Andrew|date=2011-02-09|website=Playbill|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> In the same year, the group received the Europe Theatre Prize for innovative character and originality.<ref name="europe theatre prize" />
